  Abstract

  • Homelessness is a multifaceted crisis that includes many common information challenges, such as social instability, systemic inequity, and discrimination. We combine social network analysis, Natural Language Processing (NLP), and topic modeling to measure online information sharing among homeless care organizations

  • Analyzing four years of social media data from the major federal home care communities reveals evidence of a robust-growing homeless service community interacting with the marginalized Hispanic/Latinx population shortly after the announcement of COVID-19. This study offers valuable practical policy implications for U.S. homeless services organizational learning

  Why Twitter?

  • Twitter provides a platform for engaging multiple groups, including activists, organizations, and people experiencing homelessness

  • Twitter offers immediate guidance on what to do in the event of an emergency in real-time

  • The general public, media, and NGOs heavily utilize Twitter

  • Access to Twitter is free and widely available

  • Homeless care organizations need to respond to emergencies very fast, and Twitter is one of the most accessible platforms

  Why the Hispanic/Latinx Community?

  • The US Hispanic community is overrepresented in homelessness and poverty

  • Many Spanish speakers face language barriers in health care

  • Hispanic Americans faced disproportionate health and economic impacts from COVID-19 - Hispanic workers have seen the worst employment data of any racial/ethnicity group during the COVID-19 pandemic

  • Locations where there is a large Hispanic population, such as CA, TX, and NY, had the largest increase in homeless individuals from 2019-2020


  Findings and Policy Implications for U.S. Homeless Care Organizational Learning

  • This research contributes to the understanding of the efficacy of the U.S. homeless care program by assessing online information sharing. Our analysis uncovers the emergence of a robust-growing homeless care community interacting with the U.S. Hispanic population by disseminating and sharing COVID and health-related information in both English and Spanish

  • Our findings show that Twitter has been heavily utilized during crisis events (COVID-19) to inform the general public. We see a massive shift from standard public awareness, provider care, and activist activities to COVID-19 topics and responses shortly after the announcement of the global pandemic. In the Spanish speaking information-sharing network, we see a quick shift to providing Spanish language support for COVID-19 protocols

  • Many U.S. states with a large Hispanic population, such as Texas, New York, and New Mexico, are not within the emerging Spanish information-sharing network. Homeless care organizations must consider the language barriers when fostering community engagement


  • Twitter is essential for homeless care organizations to cultivate a collaborative information-sharing environment - it provides a platform for engaging multiple groups (activists, organizations, and people experiencing homelessness). 25% of Continuum of Care homeless organizations lack a Twitter account, and they should consider using Twitter to contribute to the discussion of up-to-date community challenges


  Research Question

  • We focus on information sharing in Spanish that's targeting the U.S. Hispanic population

  • How to measure information sharing mathematically?

  • Can we observe evidence of enhanced information sharing among homeless care organizations due to the pandemic?

  Data Collection

  • We recorded a total of 473 HUD-sponsored Continuum of Care (CoC) organizations. 75% (353) of the CoC organizations have a Twitter account

  • Tweets from the CoC Twitter accounts 2 years pre-COVID and 2 years into COVID

  • Latitude and longitude of homeless care organizations

  • U.S. homeless care organization type (i.e. government vs. NGO)

  Methodology


  • Text Network Analysis. Let G = (V, E) be a graph consisting of a finite set of vertices V and edges E where each edge (\(v_i, v_j\)) is a connection between vertices. \(v_i, v_j\) ∈ V. Let V represents a collection of CoC Twitter handles. Take two random CoC Twitter handles, \(v_i\) and \(v_j\). There is a connection between \(v_i\) and \(v_j\) iff \(v_i\) and \(v_j\) share overlapping terms in their tweets. The weight of a connection between two CoC Twitter handles is defined by the sum of the Term Frequency – Inverse Document Frequency (TF-IDF) for the overlapping terms (Bail, 2016). The Louvain community detection algorithm (Blondel et al., 2008), a greedy optimization method, is applied to the text network to identify communities. The approach connects CoC Twitter handles based on the similarities of the type of vocabulary people use when tweeting. Twitter users who use similar common words are associated with weaker ties, whereas users who share similar unusual or peculiar words are connected with stronger ties.

  • STM. Topic modeling is a machine-assisted amplified reading technique to discover latent themes within an extensive collection of documents. Probabilistic topic models, notably Latent Dirichlet Allocation (Blei et al., 2003), Correlated Topic Models (Blei and Lafferty, 2007) and their extensions, have been extensively examined in recent years. The Structural Topic Model (STM) improves upon Latent Dirichlet Allocation by introducing the possibility of incorporating arbitrary metadata linked to each document (Roberts et al., 2016). STM has been widely used to model qualitative textual data in social science research, including detecting disaster events (Mishler et al., 2015), assessing students generated text in open online courses (Reich et al. 2015), evaluating open-ended survey responses (Roberts et al. 2014), and analyzing comparative politics (Lucas et al., 2015).
